INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `userId`, `title`, `standfirst`, `content`, `createdAt`, `updatedAt`, `author`, `picture`, `pictureDescription`) VALUES
(1, 1, 'Ada Lovelace, 1ère programmeuse de l\'histoire', 'Les domaines de la tech sont traditionnellement associés aux hommes et l’informatique ne faisait, jusqu’à il y a peu, pas exception à cette règle. Et pourtant, malgré cela, en plein milieu du 19ème siècle, c’est une femme qui a écris le premier programme informatique. Penchons-nous un peu plus sur l’histoire hors du commun d’Ada Lovelace...', '<p><strong>Ada Lovelace </strong>vit le jour le 10 d&eacute;cembre 1815 &agrave; Londres sous le nom de n&eacute;e <strong>Augusta </strong><strong>Ada Byron.</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Le nom de Byron vous est peut-&ecirc;tre familier, et pour cause, elle est l&rsquo;unique enfant l&eacute;gitime d&rsquo;un homme non moins illustre qu&rsquo;elle&nbsp;: le </span> po&egrave;te anglais George Gordon Byron.</p>\r\n<p>Il avait &eacute;pous&eacute; Annabella Milbanke, une femme intelligente et cultiv&eacute;e, avec qui il correspondait r&eacute;guli&egrave;rement. Elle adorait les math&eacute;matiques et Byron l&rsquo;appelait m&ecirc;me parfois &laquo;&nbsp;la princesse des parall&eacute;logrammes&raquo;</p>\r\n<p>Lorsque leur enfant naquit, c&rsquo;est Byron qui choisit ses pr&eacute;noms, le premier pr&eacute;nom, Augusta, fut choisi en hommage &agrave; Augusta Leigh, la demi-s&oelig;ur de Byron, avec qui ce dernier avait une relation incestueuse dont il eut &eacute;galement une fille, Medora, n&eacute;e le 14 avril 1814. C\'est elle qui avait encourag&eacute; Byron &agrave; se marier pour &eacute;viter un scandale, ce qu&rsquo;il avait fait &agrave; contrec&oelig;ur, en janvier 1815.</p>\r\n<p>Ada naquit en d&eacute;cembre de cette m&ecirc;me ann&eacute;e et Annabella quitta Byron le 16 janvier 1816, gardant Ada avec elle, effray&eacute;e par les acc&egrave;s de col&egrave;re et soup&ccedil;onnant son &eacute;poux d&rsquo;&ecirc;tre d&eacute;ment.</p>\r\n<p>Le 21 avril, Byron signa l\'acte de s&eacute;paration et quitta le Royaume-Uni pour toujours. Il ne les revit jamais mais fit en sorte que les tuteurs d\'Ada lui donnent une &eacute;ducation approfondie en math&eacute;matiques et en sciences, ce qui &eacute;tait tout &agrave; fait inhabituel &agrave; l\'&eacute;poque dans l\'&eacute;ducation d\'une jeune fille de la noblesse.</p>\r\n<h3>Naissance d&rsquo;une scientifique reconnue</h3>\r\n<p>En 1832, Ada rencontre Mary Somerville, &eacute;minente chercheuse et auteur scientifique du XIXe&nbsp;si&egrave;cle, qui l\'encourage et l\'aide &agrave; progresser en math&eacute;matiques. Le 5 juin 1833, Mary lui pr&eacute;sente Charles Babbage, et Ada &mdash;&nbsp;alors &acirc;g&eacute;e de 17 ans&nbsp;&mdash; est imm&eacute;diatement fascin&eacute;e par ses machines &agrave; calcul. Ils deviennent tr&egrave;s proches, Ada semblant trouver en Babbage le p&egrave;re qu\'elle n\'avait jamais eu. Parmi ses autres connaissances, on compte David Brewster, Charles Wheatstone, Charles Dickens et Michael Faraday.</p>\r\n<p>Ada se marie en 1835 avec William King, 1<sup>er</sup>&nbsp;comte de Lovelace. Ils auront trois enfants&nbsp;: Byron, Annabella (Anne Blunt) et Ralph Gordon. William &eacute;tait d&eacute;vou&eacute; &agrave; Ada et encourageait ses go&ucirc;ts et activit&eacute;s en math&eacute;matiques. La famille v&eacute;cut &agrave; Ockham Park, &agrave; Okham. Son titre et son nom complet furent pendant la plus grande partie de sa vie <em>La tr&egrave;s honorable Augusta Ada, comtesse de Lovelace </em><span style=\"font-style: normal;\">mais elle fut</span> plus connue sous le nom d&rsquo;<em>Ada Lovelace</em> ou <em>Lady Lovelace</em>.</p>\r\n<p>La sant&eacute; fragile d\'Ada, mise &agrave; l\'&eacute;preuve par les grossesses, ainsi que ses responsabilit&eacute;s de m&egrave;re et de ma&icirc;tresse de maison, la tiennent &eacute;cart&eacute;e de ses activit&eacute;s math&eacute;matiques.Malgr&eacute; les difficult&eacute;s, elle &eacute;prouve le besoin de reprendre l\'&eacute;tude des math&eacute;matiques et demande &agrave; Babbage de lui recommander un tuteur. Ce sera le c&eacute;l&egrave;bre math&eacute;maticien Auguste De Morgan qui acceptera cette charge. Il l&rsquo;aidera, par ses retours positifs, &agrave; prendre confiance dans ses capacit&eacute;s en math&eacute;matiques. Ada se r&eacute;v&egrave;le &ecirc;tre une &eacute;l&egrave;ve enthousiaste et cr&eacute;ative, pleine d&rsquo;une &eacute;nergie in&eacute;puisable et insatiable. Elle trouve, dans les math&eacute;matiques, un sens &agrave; sa vie.</p>\r\n<h3>M&eacute;moire sur la machine de Babbage</h3>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">C&rsquo;est vers la fin de 1842 qu&rsquo;elle tournera enti&egrave;rement son travail vers la machine analytique de Babbage.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Alors que Babbage est malade et sans lui en parler au pr&eacute;alable, Ada passera neuf mois &agrave; traduire l&rsquo;article que le math&eacute;maticien italien Louis-Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric M&eacute;nabr&eacute;a a publi&eacute; en fran&ccedil;ais dans un journal suisse. C&rsquo;est sur la proposition de Charles Wheatstone qu&rsquo;&eacute;tait n&eacute; le projet de faire para&icirc;tre cette traduction dans le journal <em>Scientific Memoirs,</em> sp&eacute;cialis&eacute; dans les articles scientifiques &eacute;trangers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Son mentor regretta qu&rsquo;elle n&rsquo;ait pas elle-m&ecirc;me &eacute;crit un m&eacute;moire pour pr&eacute;senter la machine analytique et lui proposa alors d\'augmenter la traduction avec des notes d&eacute;veloppant et commentant certains aspects du m&eacute;moire, id&eacute;e adopt&eacute;e avec enthousiasme par Ada.</p>\r\n<p>En collaboration &eacute;troite avec Charles Babbage qui annota les brouillons, corrigea les incompr&eacute;hensions tout en encourageant et f&eacute;licitant Ada de son travail. Elle ajouta &agrave; cet article sept notes, labellis&eacute;es de A &agrave; G, repr&eacute;sentant pr&egrave;s de trois fois le volume de texte de l\'article original.</p>\r\n<p>La note G s\'appuie sur un v&eacute;ritable algorithme tr&egrave;s d&eacute;taill&eacute; pour calculer les nombres de Bernoulli avec la machine. Le programme qui en r&eacute;sulte est souvent consid&eacute;r&eacute; comme le premier v&eacute;ritable programme informatique au monde, car les algorithmes d&eacute;crits jusque-l&agrave; n\'&eacute;taient pas d&eacute;crits avec un formalisme, dans un langage v&eacute;ritablement destin&eacute; &agrave; &ecirc;tre ex&eacute;cut&eacute; sur une machine.</p>\r\n<p>Ce programme comporte la premi&egrave;re boucle conditionnelle, v&eacute;ritable concept informatique, contrairement aux programmes s&eacute;quentiels qui avaient pu &ecirc;tre faits auparavant par Babbage, ou dans les m&eacute;tiers &agrave; tisser Jacquard.</p>\r\n<p>Ada d&eacute;montre une profonde compr&eacute;hension de la machine dans sa traduction et ses notes, et des lettres entre Babbage et Ada semblent indiquer que le r&ocirc;le de Babbage s\'est limit&eacute; &agrave; fournir les formules math&eacute;matiques. De plus, on n\'a jamais retrouv&eacute;, dans les documents et publications de Babbage, des algorithmes aussi complexes et aussi propres que celui sous-jacent au programme de calcul des nombres de Bernoulli. (il avait compil&eacute; 446 calculs possibles avec sa machine analytique mais on ne trouve plus de travaux de Babbage sur les algorithmes post&eacute;rieurs &agrave; 1840)</p>\r\n<p>Ces &eacute;l&eacute;ments laissent penser qu\'Ada Lovelace a con&ccedil;u ce programme, avec la simple supervision bienveillante de Babbage.</p>\r\n<p>Dans d\'autres notes, Ada Lovelace montre une perception des potentialit&eacute;s de la machine que Doron Swade consid&egrave;re comme &laquo;&nbsp;visionnaire, m&ecirc;me dans une perspective moderne&nbsp;&raquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Babbage avait une vision de sa machine comme &eacute;tant tourn&eacute;e vers le calcul num&eacute;rique et, &agrave; la limite, alg&eacute;brique avec la possibilit&eacute; de manipuler des symboles plut&ocirc;t que des chiffres. Il n\'a cependant rien publi&eacute; en ce sens, pr&eacute;f&eacute;rant au contraire imaginer un autre type de machine sp&eacute;cifique pour les calculs alg&eacute;briques.</p>\r\n<p>En revanche, Ada Lovelace d&eacute;crivit explicitement des possibilit&eacute;s allant au-del&agrave; d\'un contexte math&eacute;matique, comme l\'hypoth&egrave;se que &laquo;&nbsp;la machine pourrait composer de mani&egrave;re scientifique et &eacute;labor&eacute;e des morceaux de musique de n\'importe quelle longueur ou degr&eacute; de complexit&eacute;&nbsp;&raquo;.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Ada entrevit</span><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"> </span><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">ainsi </span><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">certaines possibilit&eacute;s offertes par les calculateurs universels, allant bien au-del&agrave; du calcul num&eacute;rique et de ce qu\'imaginaient Babbage et ses contemporains. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Il fallut attendre les ann&eacute;es 1930 avec Alan Turing pour formaliser une telle notion de calculateur universel qui manipule des symboles g&eacute;n&eacute;raux, et abandonner la notion de calculatrice purement num&eacute;rique.</p>\r\n<h3>Ruine et mort</h3>\r\n<p>Dans l&rsquo;espoir de subventionner les projets de Babbage, qui n\'avaient pas obtenu de financement du gouvernement britannique, Lady Lovelace se mit &agrave; jouer. Elle travailla &agrave; un syst&egrave;me qui devait lui permettre de remporter les paris du derby d\'Epsom mais ne l\'entra&icirc;na que dans l\'accumulation de dettes.</p>\r\n<p>Ada, Comtesse de Lovelace, mourut, <span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">le 27 novembre 1852, </span>&agrave; l\'&acirc;ge de 36 ans, d\'un cancer de l\'ut&eacute;rus, dans d\'horribles souffrances. Elle fut enterr&eacute;e conform&eacute;ment &agrave; son souhait pr&egrave;s de son p&egrave;re qu\'elle n\'avait jamais connu, &agrave; l\'&eacute;glise Sainte Marie Magdalene de Hucknall, &agrave; Newstead Abbey, dans le comt&eacute; de Nottingham.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"western\">Notori&eacute;t&eacute; posthume</h3>\r\n<p>Tomb&eacute;s dans l\'oubli, Ada Lovelace et ses travaux furent exhum&eacute;s avec l\'av&egrave;nement de l\'informatique. Et c\'est en son hommage qu\'on a appel&eacute; Ada le langage de programmation con&ccedil;u entre 1977 et 1983 pour le d&eacute;partement de la D&eacute;fense am&eacute;ricain (DoD).</p>\r\n<p>Ada Lovelace est consid&eacute;r&eacute;e par les historiens de l\'informatique comme la premi&egrave;re personne &agrave; avoir programm&eacute; de l\'histoire. On peut voir notamment son portrait sur les hologrammes d\'authentification des produits Microsoft.</p>\r\n<p>Ada Lovelace a &eacute;galement donn&eacute; son nom &agrave; la premi&egrave;re &eacute;cole d\'informatique f&eacute;ministe <em>Ada Tech School</em>, cr&eacute;&eacute;e en 2019 &agrave; Paris.</p>\r\n<h3>Dans la fiction</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Ada est l\'un des personnages principaux de l\'histoire alternative <em>La Machine &agrave; diff&eacute;rences</em> de Bruce Sterling et William Gibson, qui d&eacute;crit un monde dans lequel la machine de Babbage aurait &eacute;t&eacute; produite de mani&egrave;re industrielle et o&ugrave; l\'&egrave;re informatique aurait commenc&eacute; un si&egrave;cle plus t&ocirc;t.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Le film <em>Conceiving Ada&nbsp;(en)</em> (1997), r&eacute;alis&eacute; par Lynn Hershman Leeson, &eacute;tablit un parall&egrave;le entre l\'existence d\'une Britannique contemporaine et la biographie d\'Ada Lovelace (interpr&eacute;t&eacute;e par Tilda Swinton).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Le personnage d\'<em>Ada</em>, une petite fille dou&eacute;e en math&eacute;matiques, dans la bande dessin&eacute;e <em>Nombre</em>, par Egger et Thierry Smolderen, est un clin d\'&oelig;il &agrave; Ada Lovelace.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Le personnage de <em>Ada Enigma</em>, jeune fille libre et ind&eacute;pendante, dans la s&eacute;rie homonyme, par Vincent Dutreuil et Fran&ccedil;ois Maingoval, doit son nom &agrave; un clin d\'&oelig;il &agrave; Ada Lovelace et &agrave; la machine Enigma.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Le nom d\'Ada Byron a &eacute;t&eacute; choisi par la 37<sup>e</sup>&nbsp;promotion (2007/2008) des &eacute;l&egrave;ves attach&eacute;s charg&eacute;s du traitement de l\'information de l\'IRA (Institut r&eacute;gional d\'administration) de Lille.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">ADA est le nom de l\'intelligence artificielle qui copilote le robot Jehuty dans le jeu vid&eacute;o <em>Zone of the Enders</em>, la voix synth&eacute;tique d\'ADA ayant une tessiture f&eacute;minine.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Lady Ada Lovelace est un personnage expert en machine de calcul et une thaumaturge &eacute;m&eacute;rite dans le jeu de r&ocirc;le steampunk <em>Castle Falkenstein</em> de Mike Pondsmith.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"margin-bottom: 0cm;\">Lovelace (Lovey) est une intelligence artificielle, personnage &agrave; part enti&egrave;re du roman <em>L\'Espace d\'un an</em>, de Becky Chambers.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Ada Lovelace, d\'abord pr&eacute;sent&eacute;e sous son nom de jeune fille Ada Gordon (car l\'action la concernant se d&eacute;roule en 1834), apparait dans l\'&eacute;pisode 2 de la saison 12 de <em>Doctor Who</em>, <em>La Chute des espions&nbsp;: partie 2</em>. Elle accompagne le Docteur &agrave; travers diverses &eacute;poques (la sienne, 1943 et le pr&eacute;sent) pour lutter face &agrave; une crise mondiale men&eacute;e par le Ma&icirc;tre.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>', '2021-02-15 16:59:45', '2021-04-26 17:36:03', 'Emilie', 'cb32a7d4a91fAda_Byron_daguerreotype_by_Antoine_Claudet_1843_or_1850_-_cropped.png', '            Daguerrotype d\'Ada_Byron par Antoine Claudet en 1843 ou 1850            '),
(2, 1, 'Alan Turing, entre agent secret et chasseur de réplicants ?', 'Alan Turing  est l’auteur de travaux qui ont fondé scientifiquement l\'informatique mais cet homme est loin de se limiter à cela. Sans ce génie, la seconde guerre mondiale n’aurait peut être pas connu la même issue. Sa vie fut portée à l’écran 2014 dans le biopic Imitation Game, avec Benedict Cumberbatch dans le rôle de Turing. Voilà son histoire…', '<h3>Enfance et jeunesse</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Alan Mathison Turing</strong> est n&eacute; le 23 juin 1912 &agrave; Londres.</p>\r\n<p>Tr&egrave;s t&ocirc;t, le jeune Turing montre les signes de son g&eacute;nie. On relate qu\'il apprit seul &agrave; lire en trois semaines. De m&ecirc;me, il montra une affinit&eacute; pr&eacute;coce pour les chiffres et les &eacute;nigmes.</p>\r\n<p>&Agrave; la Sherborne School, Turing se lie en 1927 d\'une grande amiti&eacute; avec son camarade Christopher Morcom, passionn&eacute; de sciences et de math&eacute;matiques comme lui qui a &eacute;t&eacute; d&eacute;crit comme le \"premier amour\" de Turing. Quand Morcom meurt en f&eacute;vrier 1930 des complications de la tuberculose bovine contract&eacute;e apr&egrave;s avoir bu du lait de vache infect&eacute;, Turing, bien que mat&eacute;rialiste et ath&eacute;e, n\'admet pas la disparition compl&egrave;te d\'un esprit aussi brillant. Persuad&eacute; que l\'esprit de Morcom continue &agrave; exister, il d&eacute;cide d\'incarner le destin scientifique qu\'aurait d&ucirc; avoir Morcom.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"western\"><a name=\".C3.89tudes_sup.C3.A9rieures_et_travaux_sur_la_calculabilit.C3.A9\"></a><a name=\"&Eacute;tudes_sup&eacute;rieures_et_travaux_sur_la_calculabilit&eacute;\"></a> &Eacute;tudes sup&eacute;rieures et travaux sur la calculabilit&eacute;</h3>\r\n<p>Sa pr&eacute;f&eacute;rence pour les mati&egrave;res scientifiques fait &eacute;chouer Turing &agrave; plusieurs reprises &agrave; ses examens, faute d\'effort dans les mati&egrave;res classiques. Il n\'est admis qu\'au King\'s College de l\'universit&eacute; de Cambridge, alors qu\'il avait demand&eacute; Trinity College en premier choix. En 1935, Turing est &eacute;lu <em>fellow</em> du King\'s College, l\'&eacute;quivalent d\'une bourse de th&egrave;se, gr&acirc;ce &agrave; sa d&eacute;monstration du th&eacute;or&egrave;me central limite.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"cite_ref-11\"></a>En 1928, l\'Allemand David Hilbert &eacute;nonce le probl&egrave;me de la d&eacute;cision &mdash;&nbsp;connu sous le nom allemand d\'<span lang=\"de-DE\">&laquo;&nbsp;Entscheidungsproblem&nbsp;&raquo;</span>. Pour cela il se place dans les th&eacute;ories axiomatiques et demande s\'il est possible de trouver une m&eacute;thode &laquo;&nbsp;effectivement calculable&nbsp;&raquo; pour d&eacute;cider si une proposition est d&eacute;montrable. Pour r&eacute;soudre ce probl&egrave;me, il faut caract&eacute;riser ce qu\'est un proc&eacute;d&eacute; effectivement calculable. C\'est ce que fait Turing dans son remarquable article de 1936, <span lang=\"en-US\">&laquo;&nbsp;On Computable Numbers, with an Application to the Entscheidungsproblem&nbsp;&raquo;</span>, en imaginant, non une machine mat&eacute;rielle, mais un &laquo;&nbsp;&ecirc;tre calculant&nbsp;&raquo;, qui peut &ecirc;tre indiff&eacute;remment un appareil logique tr&egrave;s simple ou un humain bien disciplin&eacute; appliquant des r&egrave;gles &mdash;&nbsp;comme le faisaient les employ&eacute;s des bureaux de calcul ou les artilleurs &agrave; l\'&eacute;poque.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"cite_ref-CNRS_14-0\"></a>Dans le cours de son raisonnement, il d&eacute;montre que le probl&egrave;me de l\'arr&ecirc;t d&rsquo;une machine de Turing ne peut &ecirc;tre r&eacute;solu par algorithme&nbsp;: il n&rsquo;est pas possible de d&eacute;cider avec un algorithme (c&rsquo;est-&agrave;-dire avec une machine de Turing) si une machine de Turing donn&eacute;e s&rsquo;arr&ecirc;tera. Bien que sa preuve ait &eacute;t&eacute; publi&eacute;e apr&egrave;s celle d\'Alonzo Church, le travail de Turing est plus accessible et intuitif.</p>\r\n<p>Il est aussi compl&egrave;tement nouveau dans sa pr&eacute;sentation du concept de &laquo;&nbsp;machine universelle&nbsp;&raquo; (de Turing), avec l\'id&eacute;e qu\'une telle machine puisse accomplir les t&acirc;ches de n\'importe quelle autre machine. L\'article pr&eacute;sente &eacute;galement la notion de nombre r&eacute;el calculable. Il d&eacute;duit de l\'ind&eacute;cidabilit&eacute; du probl&egrave;me de l\'arr&ecirc;t que l\'on peut d&eacute;finir des nombres r&eacute;els qui ne sont pas calculables. Il introduit les concepts de programme et de programmation.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"cite_ref-19\"></a>Turing passe la plus grande partie de 1937 et de 1938 &agrave; travailler sur divers sujets &agrave; l\'universit&eacute; de Princeton, sous la direction du logicien Alonzo Church. Il obtient en mai 1938 son Ph. D. de l\'universit&eacute; de Princeton&nbsp;; son manuscrit pr&eacute;sente la notion d\'hypercalcul, o&ugrave; les machines de Turing sont compl&eacute;t&eacute;es par ce qu\'il appelle des oracles, autorisant ainsi l\'&eacute;tude de probl&egrave;mes qui ne peuvent pas &ecirc;tre r&eacute;solus de mani&egrave;re algorithmique. Church emploie pour la premi&egrave;re fois l\'expression &laquo;&nbsp;machine de Turing&nbsp;&raquo; dans le compte rendu de la th&egrave;se de son &eacute;l&egrave;ve dans le <em>Journal of Symbolic Logic</em>.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"western\"><a name=\"Cryptanalyse\"></a>Cryptanalyse</h3>\r\n<p><a name=\"cite_ref-Hinsley-GuerreEcourt&eacute;e2ans_24-0\"></a>Selon plusieurs historiens, le travail de Turing pour d&eacute;chiffrer le code des transmissions allemandes permit de raccourcir la Seconde Guerre mondiale de deux ans.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"cite_ref-25\"></a>Fin 1938, apr&egrave;s les accords de Munich, la Grande-Bretagne comprend le danger du nazisme, et d&eacute;veloppe ses armements. Turing fait partie des jeunes cerveaux appel&eacute;s &agrave; suivre des cours de chiffre et de cryptanalyse &agrave; la Government Code and Cypher School (GC&amp;CS). Juste avant la d&eacute;claration de guerre, il rejoint le centre secret de la GC&amp;CS &agrave; Bletchley Park. Il y est affect&eacute; aux &eacute;quipes charg&eacute;es du d&eacute;chiffrage des messages cod&eacute;s avec les machines Enigma utilis&eacute;es par les forces arm&eacute;es allemandes. Ce travail profite initialement des perc&eacute;es effectu&eacute;es par les services secrets polonais du Biuro Szyfr&oacute;w22 et du renseignement fran&ccedil;ais au PC Bruno, que Turing visite entre d&eacute;cembre 1939 et les premiers mois de 1940 et d\'o&ugrave; il rapporte des copies des feuilles de Zygalski. Mais, en mai 1940, les Allemands perfectionnent leur syst&egrave;me cryptographique. Turing participe aux recherches qui permettent de p&eacute;n&eacute;trer les r&eacute;seaux de l\'arm&eacute;e de terre et de l\'aviation. Il con&ccedil;oit des m&eacute;thodes math&eacute;matiques et des versions am&eacute;lior&eacute;es de la &laquo;&nbsp;Bombe&nbsp;&raquo; polonaise, machine &eacute;lectrom&eacute;canique permettant d\'essayer rapidement des ensembles de cl&eacute;s potentielles sur des blocs de communication d\'Enigma. Une fois l\'affaire lanc&eacute;e, Turing prend la t&ecirc;te de l\'&eacute;quipe charg&eacute;e de trouver les cl&eacute;s bien plus herm&eacute;tiques des r&eacute;seaux de l\'Enigma navale. Ces perc&eacute;es d&eacute;cisives redonnent &agrave; la Grande-Bretagne un avantage temporaire dans les batailles d\'Angleterre, de Libye et de l\'Atlantique.</p>\r\n<p><a name=\"cite_ref-26\"></a><a name=\"cite_ref-27\"></a>Jusqu\'au milieu des ann&eacute;es 1970, seuls quelques anciens cryptanalystes fran&ccedil;ais et polonais avaient publi&eacute; quelques informations sur la lutte contre Enigma dans leurs pays respectifs&nbsp;; les capacit&eacute;s de d&eacute;cryptage de Bletchley Park et l\'op&eacute;ration Ultra restaient un secret militaire absolu en Grande-Bretagne. Puis les autorit&eacute;s britanniques d&eacute;classifi&egrave;rent progressivement les techniques de d&eacute;cryptage d\'Enigma jusqu\'&agrave; 2000.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"western\"><a name=\"Travail_sur_les_premiers_ordinateurs\"></a> Travail sur les premiers ordinateurs</h3>\r\n<p>Apr&egrave;s la guerre, Turing travaille au National Physical Laboratory. Fin 1945, apr&egrave;s avoir lu le rapport von Neumann qui d&eacute;crit la structure g&eacute;n&eacute;rale d\'un ordinateur et discute des m&eacute;thodes de programmation, Turing r&eacute;dige ce qui est sans doute le premier projet d&eacute;taill&eacute; d\'un ordinateur&nbsp;: l\'ACE (Automatic Computing Engine). Toutefois, il ne parvient pas &agrave; s\'entendre avec les ing&eacute;nieurs &eacute;lectroniciens du NPL charg&eacute;s de construire cette machine, qui soul&egrave;vent des objections techniques et pr&eacute;f&egrave;rent commencer par un prototype plus modeste.</p>\r\n<p>&Agrave; la rentr&eacute;e 1948, il est appel&eacute; par Max Newman, son ancien professeur de logique &agrave; Cambridge et coll&egrave;gue &agrave; Bletchley Park, &agrave; l\'universit&eacute; de Manchester o&ugrave; Max Newman, inspir&eacute; lui aussi par le rapport von Neumann, dirige le d&eacute;veloppement de l\'un des tout premiers v&eacute;ritables ordinateurs&nbsp;: Manchester Mark I, industrialis&eacute; ensuite par la firme Ferranti. Turing devient directeur adjoint du laboratoire de calcul de l\'universit&eacute; de Manchester (titre sans grande signification), et travaille &agrave; la programmation de l\'ordinateur.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"western\"><a name=\"Vers_l.27intelligence_artificielle_:_le_test_de_Turing\"></a><a name=\"Vers_l\'intelligence_artificielle_:_le_test_de_Turing\"></a> Vers l\'intelligence artificielle&nbsp;: le test de Turing</h3>\r\n<p>Dans l\'article &laquo;&nbsp;Computing Machinery and Intelligence&nbsp;&raquo; (<em>Mind</em>, octobre 1950), Turing explore le probl&egrave;me de l\'intelligence artificielle et propose une exp&eacute;rience maintenant connue sous le nom de test de Turing, o&ugrave; il tente de d&eacute;finir une &eacute;preuve permettant de qualifier une machine de &laquo;&nbsp;consciente&nbsp;&raquo;&nbsp;; Turing fait le &laquo;&nbsp;pari que d\'ici cinquante ans, il n\'y aura plus moyen de distinguer les r&eacute;ponses donn&eacute;es par un homme ou un ordinateur, et ce sur n\'importe quel sujet&nbsp;&raquo;.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"western\"><a name=\"Condamnation\"></a>Condamnation</h3>\r\n<p>De Cambridge &agrave; Bletchley Park, Turing ne faisait aucun myst&egrave;re de son orientation sexuelle&nbsp;; ouvertement homosexuel, il ne cachait pas ses aventures. Il &eacute;tait d\'ailleurs loin d\'&ecirc;tre le seul. En 1952, sa maison de Manchester est cambriol&eacute;e. Turing porte plainte. Arr&ecirc;t&eacute;, le cambrioleur d&eacute;nonce le complice qui lui avait indiqu&eacute; l\'affaire, un ex-amant occasionnel de Turing. Celui-ci ne nie pas cette ancienne relation. Tous deux sont inculp&eacute;s d\'&laquo;&nbsp;ind&eacute;cence manifeste et de perversion sexuelle&nbsp;&raquo; d\'apr&egrave;s la Criminal Law Amendment Act (1885). Quelques ann&eacute;es plus t&ocirc;t, ce n\'aurait &eacute;t&eacute; qu\'un fait divers. Mais, au d&eacute;but des ann&eacute;es 1950, une affaire retentissante d\'espionnage scientifique au profit de l\'Union sovi&eacute;tique o&ugrave; sont impliqu&eacute;s des intellectuels anglais homosexuels surnomm&eacute;s les Cinq de Cambridge a rendu les services de contre-espionnage britanniques et am&eacute;ricains sensibles &agrave; un profil comme celui de Turing.</p>\r\n<p>Le proc&egrave;s est m&eacute;diatis&eacute;. Hugh Alexander fait de son confr&egrave;re un brillant portrait, mais il est emp&ecirc;ch&eacute; de citer ses titres de guerre par le <em>Secret Act</em>. Turing est mis en demeure de choisir&nbsp;: incarc&eacute;ration ou castration chimique r&eacute;duisant sa libido. Il choisit le traitement, d\'une dur&eacute;e d\'un an, avec des effets secondaires temporaires (le coureur &agrave; pied svelte qu\'il &eacute;tait devient gros, impuissant, ses seins grossissent comme ceux d\'une femme), et surtout des effets psychiques profond&eacute;ment d&eacute;moralisants. Alors qu\'il a &eacute;t&eacute; consacr&eacute;, en 1951, en devenant membre de la Royal Society, &agrave; partir de 1952 il est &eacute;cart&eacute; des plus grands projets scientifiques. Toutefois, en avril 1953, la &laquo;&nbsp;cure&nbsp;&raquo; se termine, ses effets s\'estompent et Turing recommence &agrave; faire des projets de recherche, de voyages en France et en M&eacute;diterran&eacute;e.</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"western\"><a name=\"Mort\"></a>Mort</h3>\r\n<p><a name=\"cite_ref-44\"></a>Le 8 juin 1954, dans l\'apr&egrave;s-midi, Turing est retrouv&eacute; par sa gouvernante, mort dans son lit, avec une pomme croqu&eacute;e sur sa table de nuit. L\'autopsie conclut &agrave; un suicide par empoisonnement au cyanure, m&ecirc;me si sa m&egrave;re tenta d\'&eacute;carter cette th&egrave;se. Le moyen d\'ingestion du poison aurait &eacute;t&eacute; cette pomme qu\'il aurait partiellement mang&eacute;e (une l&eacute;gende tenace et d&eacute;mentie y voit l\'origine du logo de la firme Apple), et qui aurait &eacute;t&eacute; pr&eacute;alablement imbib&eacute;e de cyanure&nbsp;; il n\'existe pas de certitude &agrave; cet &eacute;gard, la pomme n\'ayant pas &eacute;t&eacute; analys&eacute;e.</p>\r\n<p>Le biographe de Turing, Andrew Hodges, a &eacute;mis l\'hypoth&egrave;se que Turing aurait choisi ce mode d\'ingestion pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment afin de laisser &agrave; sa m&egrave;re la possibilit&eacute; de croire &agrave; un accident, sachant que les p&eacute;pins de pomme contiennent naturellement du cyanure mais en quantit&eacute; trop faible cependant pour avoir un effet toxique. Certains ont remarqu&eacute; le lien entre sa m&eacute;thode pr&eacute;sum&eacute;e de suicide et le film <em>Blanche-Neige et les Sept Nains</em>, dont il avait particuli&egrave;rement appr&eacute;ci&eacute; la sc&egrave;ne o&ugrave; la sorci&egrave;re empoisonne la pomme, au point de chantonner r&eacute;guli&egrave;rement les vers prononc&eacute;s par celle-ci&nbsp;: &laquo;&nbsp;Plongeons la pomme dans le chaudron, pour qu\'elle s\'impr&egrave;gne de poison&nbsp;&raquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Toutefois, Jack Copeland, sp&eacute;cialiste de Turing, estime que la mort de celui-ci est accidentelle. Il avance les arguments suivants&nbsp;: Turing ne montrait aucun signe de d&eacute;pression et, peu avant sa mort, avait not&eacute; des projets par &eacute;crit&nbsp;; il avait l\'habitude de faire des exp&eacute;riences chimiques et d&eacute;tenait du cyanure &agrave; cette fin&nbsp;; il lui arrivait d\'&ecirc;tre imprudent dans ces exp&eacute;riences, go&ucirc;tant par exemple des produits pour les identifier. Il aurait pu &eacute;galement inhaler accidentellement une solution cyanur&eacute;e qu\'il utilisait pour dissoudre de l\'or&nbsp;; c\'est de cette fa&ccedil;on que, pour Copeland, il aurait ing&eacute;r&eacute; ou inhal&eacute; une dose mortelle de cyanure.</p>\r\n<p>Dans la culture populaire, l\'id&eacute;e erron&eacute;e qu\'il se soit suicid&eacute; en raison de son homosexualit&eacute; a &eacute;t&eacute; diffus&eacute; par Richard Dawkins. Cette th&egrave;se n\'est soutenue par aucun expert d\'Alan Turing comme Jack Copelan ou Andrew Hodges. Malgr&eacute; l\'avis des experts, cette sp&eacute;culation de Richard Dawkins est largement reprise par certains journaux.</p>', '2021-02-18 19:11:57', '2021-04-26 17:35:50', 'Emilie', '5046e653eacfAlan_Turing_Aged_16.jpg', '    Photographie d\'Alan Turing à l\'âge de 16    '),
(3, 1, 'Don\'t be too proud of this technological terror you\'ve constructed.', 'Sir, if you\'ll not be needing me, I\'ll close down for awhile. Sure, go ahead. What is it? Your fathers lightsaber. This is the weapon of a Jedi Knight. Not as clumsy or as random as a blaster. An elegant weapon for a more civilized time. For over a thousand generations the Jedi Knights were the guardians of peace and justice in the Old Republic. Before the dark times, before the Empire. How did my father die? A young Jedi named Darth Vader, who was a pupil of mine until he turned to evil, helped the Empire hunt down and destroy the Jedi Knights. He betrayed and murdered your father. Now the Jedi are all but extinct. Vader was seduced by the dark side of the Force. The Force?', '<h3>General Kenobi, years ago you served my father in the Clone Wars.</h3>\r\n<p>Now he begs you to help him in his struggle against the Empire. I regret that I am unable to present my father\'s request to you in person, but my ship has fallen under attack and I\'m afraid my mission to bring you to Alderaan has failed. I have placed information vital to the survival of the Rebellion into the memory systems of this R2 unit. My father will know how to retrieve it. You must see this droid safely delivered to him on Alderaan. This is our most desperate hour. Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi, you\'re my only hope.</p>\r\n<p>Lord Vader, I should have known. Only you could be so bold. The Imperial Senate will not sit for this, when they hear you\'ve attacked a diplomatic... Don\'t play games with me, Your Highness. You weren\'t on any mercy mission this time. You passed directly through a restricted system. Several transmissions were beamed to this ship by Rebel spies. I want to know what happened to the plans they sent you. I don\'t know what you\'re talking about. I\'m a member of the Imperial Senate on a diplomatic mission to Alderaan... You\'re a part of the Rebel Alliance...and a traitor. Take her away!</p>\r\n<p>Sir, if you\'ll not be needing me, I\'ll close down for awhile. Sure, go ahead. What is it? Your fathers lightsaber. This is the weapon of a Jedi Knight. Not as clumsy or as random as a blaster. An elegant weapon for a more civilized time. For over a thousand generations the Jedi Knights were the guardians of peace and justice in the Old Republic. Before the dark times, before the Empire. How did my father die? A young Jedi named Darth Vader, who was a pupil of mine until he turned to evil, helped the Empire hunt down and destroy the Jedi Knights. He betrayed and murdered your father. Now the Jedi are all but extinct. Vader was seduced by the dark side of the Force. The Force?</p>\r\n<h3>That malfunctioning little twerp. This is all his fault!</h3>\r\n<p>He tricked me into going this way, but he\'ll do no better. Wait, what\'s that? A transport! I\'m saved! Over here! Help! Please, help! Artoo-Detoo! It\'s you! It\'s you! How did I get into this mess? I really don\'t know how. We seem to be made to suffer. It\'s our lot in life. I\'ve got to rest before I fall apart. My joints are almost frozen. What a desolate place this is. Where are you going? Well, I\'m not going that way. It\'s much too rocky. This way is much easier. What makes you think there are settlements over there? Don\'t get technical with me. What mission? What are you talking about? I\'ve had just about enough of you! Go that way! You\'ll be malfunctioning within a day, you nearsighted scrap pile! And don\'t let me catch you following me begging for help, because you won\'t get it. No more adventures. I\'m not going that way.</p>\r\n<p>Remember, a Jedi can feel the Force flowing through him. You mean it controls your actions? Partially. But it also obeys your commands. Hokey religions and ancient weapons are no match for a good blaster at your side, kid. You don\'t believe in the Force, do you? Kid, I\'ve flown from one side of this galaxy to the other. I\'ve seen a lot of strange stuff, but I\'ve never seen anything to make me believe there\'s one all-powerful force controlling everything. There\'s no mystical energy field that controls my destiny. It\'s all a lot of simple tricks and nonsense. I suggest you try it again, Luke. This time, let go your conscious self and act on instinct. With the blast shield down, I can\'t even see. How am I supposed to fight? Your eyes can deceive you. Don\'t trust them.</p>\r\n<h3>Hey, you\'re not permitted in there. It\'s restricted.</h3>\r\n<p>You\'ll be deactivated for sure.. Don\'t call me a mindless philosopher, you overweight glob of grease! Now come out before somebody sees you. Secret mission? What plans? What are you talking about? I\'m not getting in there! I\'m going to regret this. There goes another one. Hold your fire. There are no life forms. It must have been short-circuited. That\'s funny, the damage doesn\'t look as bad from out here. Are you sure this things safe?</p>\r\n<p>Don\'t be too proud of this technological terror you\'ve constructed. The ability to destroy a planet is insignificant next to the power of the Force. Don\'t try to frighten us with your sorcerer\'s ways, Lord Vader. Your sad devotion to that ancient religion has not helped you conjure up the stolen data tapes, or given you clairvoyance enough to find the Rebel\'s hidden fort... I find your lack of faith disturbing. Enough of this! Vader, release him! As you wish. This bickering is pointless. Lord Vader will provide us with the location of the Rebel fortress by the time this station is operational. We will then crush the Rebellion with one swift stroke.</p>\r\n<p>The Death Star plans are not in the main computer. Where are those transmissions you intercepted? What have you done with those plans? We intercepted no transmissions. Aaah....This is a consular ship. Were on a diplomatic mission. If this is a consular ship...were is the Ambassador? Commander, tear this ship apart until you\'ve found those plans and bring me the Ambassador. I want her alive! There she is! Set for stun! She\'ll be all right. Inform Lord Vader we have a prisoner.</p>\r\n<p>I can\'t abide these Jawas. Disgusting creatures. Go on, go on. I can\'t understand how we got by those troopers. I thought we were dead. The Force can have a strong influence on the weak-minded. You will find it a powerful ally. Do you really think we\'re going to find a pilot here that\'ll take us to Alderaan? Well, most of the best freighter pilots can be found here. Only watch your step. This place can be a little rough. I\'m ready for anything. Come along, Artoo.</p>', '2021-02-19 17:01:53', '2021-04-26 17:35:32', 'Emilie', '27daecce1f9fImage par Gerd Altmann de Pixabay-social-media-1989152_1920.jpg', '  Quelques mots associés au web écrits en noir sur fond blanc.  '),
(4, 1, 'The Death Star plans are not in the main computer.', 'Did you hear that? They\'ve shut down the main reactor. We\'ll be destroyed for sure. This is madness! We\'re doomed! There\'ll be no escape for the Princess this time. What\'s that? Artoo! Artoo-Detoo, where are you? At last! Where have you been? They\'re heading in this direction. What are we going to do? We\'ll be sent to the spice mine of Kessel or smashed into who knows what! Wait a minute, where are you going?', '<h3>Hey, whoa, just where do you think you\'re going?</h3>\r\n<p>Master Luke here is your rightful owner. We\'ll have no more of this Obi-Wan Kenobi jibberish...and don\'t talk to me about your mission, either. You\'re fortunate he doesn\'t blast you into a million pieces right here. What\'s wrong with him now? Oh my...sir, he says there are several creatures approaching from the southeast. Sandpeople! Or worst! Come on, let\'s have a look. Come on. There are two Banthas down there but I don\'t see any...wait a second, they\'re Sandpeople all right. I can see one of them now.</p>\r\n<p>Luke, take these two over to the garage, will you? I want you to have both of them cleaned up before dinner. But I was going into Toshi Station to pick up some power converters... You can waste time with your friends when your chores are done. Now come on, get to it! All right, come on! And the red one, come on. Well, come on, Red, let\'s go. Uncle Owen... Yeah?This R2 unit has a bad motivator. Look! Hey, what\'re you trying to push on us? Excuse me, sir, but that R2 unit is in prime condition. A real bargain. Uncle Owen... Yeah? What about that one? What about that blue one? We\'ll take that one. Yeah, take it away.</p>\r\n<p>Someone was in the pod. The tracks go off in this direction. Look, sir -- droids.</p>\r\n<p>What are you doing hiding there? It wasn\'t my fault, sir. Please don\'t deactivate me. I told him not to go, but he\'s faulty, malfunctioning, kept babbling on about his mission. Oh, no! That R2 unit has always been a problem. These astro-droids are getting quite out of hand. Even I can\'t understand their logic at times. How could I be so stupid? He\'s nowhere in sight. Blast it! Pardon me, sir, but couldn\'t we go after him? It\'s too dangerous with all the Sandpeople around. We\'ll have to wait until morning. Luke, I\'m shutting the power down for the night. All right, I\'ll be there in a few minutes. Boy, am I gonna get it. You know that little droid is going to cause me a lot of trouble. Oh, he excels at that, sir.</p>\r\n<h3>Well, if there\'s a bright center to the universe, you\'re on the planet that it\'s farthest from.</h3>\r\n<p>I see, sir. Uh, you can call me Luke. I see, sir Luke. Just Luke. And I am See-Threepio, human-cyborg relations, and this is my counterpart, Artoo-Detoo. Hello. You got a lot of carbon scoring here. It looks like you boys have seen a lot of action. With all we\'ve been through, sometimes I\'m amazed we\'re in as good condition as we are, what with the Rebellion and all. You know of the Rebellion against the Empire? That\'s how we came to be in your service, if you take my meaning, sir.</p>\r\n<p>Uh, I\'m quite sure you\'ll be very pleased with that one, sir. He really is in first-class condition. I\'ve worked with him before. Here he comes. Okay, let\'s go. Now, don\'t you forget this! Why I should stick my neck out for you is quite beyond my capacity!</p>\r\n<p>Thank the maker! This oil bath is going to feel so good. I\'ve got such a bad case of dust contamination, I can barely move! It just isn\'t fair. Oh, Biggs is right. I\'m never gonna get out of here! Is there anything I might do to help? Well, not unless you can alter time, speed up the harvest, or teleport me off this rock! I don\'t think so, sir. I\'m only a droid and not very knowledgeable about such things. Not on this planet, anyways. As a matter of fact, I\'m not even sure which planet I\'m on.</p>\r\n<h3>Owen, he can\'t stay here forever.</h3>\r\n<p>Most of his friends have gone. It means so much to him. I\'ll make it up to him next year. I promise. Luke\'s just not a farmer, Owen. He has too much of his father in him. That\'s what I\'m afraid of.</p>\r\n<p>Obi-Wan Kenobi...Obi-Wan? Now thats a name I haven\'t heard in a long time...a long time. I think my uncle knew him. He said he was dead. Oh, he\'s not dead, not...not yet. You know him! Well of course, of course I know him. He\'s me! I haven\'t gone by the name Obi-Wan since oh, before you were born. Then the droid does belong to you. Don\'t seem to remember ever owning a droid. Very interesting... I think we better get indoors. The Sandpeople are easily startled but they will soon be back and in greater numbers. Threepio! Where am I? I must have taken a bad step... Can you stand? We\'ve got to get out of here before the Sandpeople return. I don\'t think I can make it. You go on, Master Luke. There\'s no sense in you risking yourself on my account. I\'m done for. No, you\'re not. What kind of talk is that? Quickly, son...they\'re on the move.</p>\r\n<p>Luke? Luke? Luke? Have you seen Luke this morning? He said he had some things to do before he started today, so he left early. Uh? Did he take those two new droids with him? I think so. Well, he\'d better have those units in the south range repaired be midday or there\'ll be hell to pay! Wait, there\'s something dead ahead on the scanner. It looks like our droid...hit the accelerator.</p>\r\n<p>Wake up! Wake up! We\'re doomed. Do you think they\'ll melt us down? Don\'t shoot! Don\'t shoot! Will this never end?</p>\r\n<p>Luke, tell Owen that if he gets a translator to be sure it speaks Bocce. It looks like we don\'t have much of a choice but I\'ll remind him. I have no need for a protocol droid. Sir -- not in an environment such as this -- that\'s why I\'ve also been programmed for over thirty secondary functions that... What I really need is a droid that understands the binary language of moisture vaporators. Vaporators! Sir -- My first job was programming binary load lifter...very similar to your vaporators. You could say... Do you speak Bocce? Of course I can, sir. It\'s like a second language for me...I\'m as fluent in... All right shut up! I\'ll take this one.</p>', '2021-02-19 17:03:29', '2021-04-26 17:35:12', 'Emilie', '69c3f3f96fe9geralt-pixabay-binary-code-63529_1920.jpg', '  0 et 1 formant une spirale.  '),
(5, 1, 'You know, I think that R2 unit we bought might have been stolen. ', '   Open up in there! Oh, no! There isn\'t any other way out. I can\'t hold them off forever! Now what? This is some rescue. When you came in here, didn\'t you have a plan for getting out? He\'s the brains, sweetheart. Well, I didn\'t... What the hell are you doing? Somebody has to save our skins. Into the garbage chute, wise guy. Get in there you big furry oaf! I don\'t care what you smell! Get in there and don\'t worry about it. Wonderful girl! Either I\'m going to kill her or I\'m beginning to like her. Get in there!   ', '<h3><strong>Threepio! Come in, Threepio! Threepio! </strong></h3>\r\n<p>Get to the top! I can\'t Where could he be? Threepio! Threepio, will you come in? They aren\'t here! Something must have happened to them. See if they\'ve been captured. Hurry! One thing\'s for sure. We\'re all going to be a lot thinner! Get on top of it! I\'m trying! Thank goodness, they haven\'t found them! Where could they be? Use the comlink? Oh, my! I forgot I turned it off! Are you there, sir? Threepio! We\'ve had some problems... Will you shut up and listen to me? Shut down all garbage mashers on the detention level, will you? Do you copy? Shut down all the garbage mashers on the detention level. Shut down all the garbage mashers on the detention level. No. Shut them all down! Hurry! Listen to them! They\'re dying, Artoo! Curse my metal body! I wasn\'t fast enough. It\'s all my fault! My poor master! Threepio, we\'re all right! We\'re all right. You did great.</p>\r\n<p>How did I get into this mess? I really don\'t know how. We seem to be made to suffer. It\'s our lot in life. I\'ve got to rest before I fall apart. My joints are almost frozen. What a desolate place this is. Where are you going? Well, I\'m not going that way. It\'s much too rocky. This way is much easier. What makes you think there are settlements over there? Don\'t get technical with me. What mission? What are you talking about? I\'ve had just about enough of you! Go that way! You\'ll be malfunctioning within a day, you nearsighted scrap pile! And don\'t let me catch you following me begging for help, because you won\'t get it. No more adventures. I\'m not going that way.</p>\r\n<h3>Oh! The garbage chute was a really wonderful idea.</h3>\r\n<p>What an incredible smell you\'ve discovered! Let\'s get out of here! Get away from there... No! wait! Will you forget it? I already tried it. It\'s magnetically sealed! Put that thing away! You\'re going to get us all killed. Absolutely, Your Worship. Look, I had everything under control until you led us down here. You know, it\'s not going to take them long to figure out what happened to us. It could be worst... It\'s worst. There\'s something alive in here! That\'s your imagination. Something just moves past my leg! Look! Did you see that? What? Help!</p>\r\n<p>Someone was in the pod. The tracks go off in this direction. Look, sir -- droids.</p>\r\n<p>The Death Star plans are not in the main computer. Where are those transmissions you intercepted? What have you done with those plans? We intercepted no transmissions. Aaah....This is a consular ship. Were on a diplomatic mission. If this is a consular ship...were is the Ambassador? Commander, tear this ship apart until you\'ve found those plans and bring me the Ambassador. I want her alive! There she is! Set for stun! She\'ll be all right. Inform Lord Vader we have a prisoner. Hey, you\'re not permitted in there. It\'s restricted. You\'ll be deactivated for sure.. Don\'t call me a mindless philosopher, you overweight glob of grease! Now come out before somebody sees you. Secret mission? What plans? What are you talking about? I\'m not getting in there! I\'m going to regret this. There goes another one. Hold your fire. There are no life forms. It must have been short-circuited.</p>\r\n<h3>That\'s funny, the damage doesn\'t look as bad from out here.</h3>\r\n<p>Are you sure this things safe? That malfunctioning little twerp. This is all his fault! He tricked me into going this way, but he\'ll do no better. Wait, what\'s that? A transport! I\'m saved! Over here! Help! Please, help! Artoo-Detoo! It\'s you! It\'s you! Did you hear that? They\'ve shut down the main reactor. We\'ll be destroyed for sure. This is madness! We\'re doomed! There\'ll be no escape for the Princess this time. What\'s that? Artoo! Artoo-Detoo, where are you? At last! Where have you been? They\'re heading in this direction. What are we going to do? We\'ll be sent to the spice mine of Kessel or smashed into who knows what! Wait a minute, where are you going? Look at the size of that thing!</p>\r\n<p>Cut the chatter, Red Two. Accelerate to attack speed. This is it, boys! Red Leader, this is Gold Leader. I copy, Gold Leader. We\'re starting for the target shaft now. We\'re in position. I\'m going to cut across the axis and try and draw their fire. Heavy fire, boss! Twenty-degrees. I see it. Stay low. This is Red Five, I\'m going in! Luke, pull up! Are you all right? I got a little cooked, but I\'m okay.</p>\r\n<p>Holding her is dangerous. If word of this gets out, it could generate sympathy for the Rebellion in the senate. I have traced the Rebel spies to her. Now she is my only link to find their secret base! She\'ll die before she tells you anything. Leave that to me. Send a distress signal and then inform the senate that all aboard were killed! Lord Vader, the battle station plans are not aboard this ship! And no transmissions were made. An escape pod was jettisoned during the fighting, but no life forms were aboard. She must have hidden the plans in the escape pod. Send a detachment down to retrieve them. See to it personally, Commander. There\'ll be no one to stop us this time. Yes, sir.</p>', '2021-03-03 20:01:41', '2021-04-26 17:34:56', 'Emilie', '593ca09b2ac8pexels-markus-spiske-1972464.jpg', '     Des lignes de code sur un écran incliné vers le coin supérieur droit.    ');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `userId`, `title`, `standfirst`, `content`, `createdAt`, `updatedAt`, `author`, `picture`, `pictureDescription`) VALUES
(35, 1, 'We\'ve got to find out which cell this princess of yours is in.', 'Here it is...cell twenty-one-eight-seven. You go get her. I\'ll hold them here. Everything is under control. Situation normal. What happened? Uh...had a slight weapons malfunction. But, uh, everything\'s perfectly all right now. We\'re fine. We\'re all fine here, now, thank you. How are you? We\'re sending a squad up. Uh, uh, negative. We had a reactor leak here now. Give us a few minutes to lock it down. Large leak...very dangerous. Who is this? What\'s your operating number? Boring conversation anyway. Luke! We\'re going to have company!', '<h3>Holding her is dangerous.</h3>\r\n<p>If word of this gets out, it could generate sympathy for the Rebellion in the senate. I have traced the Rebel spies to her. Now she is my only link to find their secret base! She\'ll die before she tells you anything. Leave that to me. Send a distress signal and then inform the senate that all aboard were killed! Lord Vader, the battle station plans are not aboard this ship! And no transmissions were made. An escape pod was jettisoned during the fighting, but no life forms were aboard. She must have hidden the plans in the escape pod. Send a detachment down to retrieve them. See to it personally, Commander. There\'ll be no one to stop us this time. Yes, sir.</p>\r\n<p>That malfunctioning little twerp. This is all his fault! He tricked me into going this way, but he\'ll do no better. Wait, what\'s that? A transport! I\'m saved! Over here! Help! Please, help! Artoo-Detoo! It\'s you! It\'s you!</p>\r\n<p>Someone was in the pod. The tracks go off in this direction. Look, sir -- droids.</p>\r\n<h3>How did I get into this mess?</h3>\r\n<p>I really don\'t know how. We seem to be made to suffer. It\'s our lot in life. I\'ve got to rest before I fall apart. My joints are almost frozen. What a desolate place this is. Where are you going? Well, I\'m not going that way. It\'s much too rocky. This way is much easier. What makes you think there are settlements over there? Don\'t get technical with me. What mission? What are you talking about? I\'ve had just about enough of you! Go that way! You\'ll be malfunctioning within a day, you nearsighted scrap pile! And don\'t let me catch you following me begging for help, because you won\'t get it. No more adventures. I\'m not going that way.</p>\r\n<p>The Death Star plans are not in the main computer. Where are those transmissions you intercepted? What have you done with those plans? We intercepted no transmissions. Aaah....This is a consular ship. Were on a diplomatic mission. If this is a consular ship...were is the Ambassador? Commander, tear this ship apart until you\'ve found those plans and bring me the Ambassador. I want her alive! There she is! Set for stun! She\'ll be all right. Inform Lord Vader we have a prisoner.</p>\r\n<h3>Did you hear that?</h3>\r\n<p>They\'ve shut down the main reactor. We\'ll be destroyed for sure. This is madness! We\'re doomed! There\'ll be no escape for the Princess this time. What\'s that? Artoo! Artoo-Detoo, where are you? At last! Where have you been? They\'re heading in this direction. What are we going to do? We\'ll be sent to the spice mine of Kessel or smashed into who knows what! Wait a minute, where are you going?</p>\r\n<p>Lord Vader, I should have known. Only you could be so bold. The Imperial Senate will not sit for this, when they hear you\'ve attacked a diplomatic... Don\'t play games with me, Your Highness. You weren\'t on any mercy mission this time. You passed directly through a restricted system. Several transmissions were beamed to this ship by Rebel spies. I want to know what happened to the plans they sent you. I don\'t know what you\'re talking about. I\'m a member of the Imperial Senate on a diplomatic mission to Alderaan... You\'re a part of the Rebel Alliance...and a traitor. Take her away!</p>\r\n<p>Hey, you\'re not permitted in there. It\'s restricted. You\'ll be deactivated for sure.. Don\'t call me a mindless philosopher, you overweight glob of grease! Now come out before somebody sees you. Secret mission? What plans? What are you talking about? I\'m not getting in there! I\'m going to regret this. There goes another one. Hold your fire. There are no life forms. It must have been short-circuited. That\'s funny, the damage doesn\'t look as bad from out here. Are you sure this things safe?</p>\r\n<h3>Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi. You\'re my only hope.</h3>\r\n<p>What\'s this? What is what?!? He asked you a question... What is that? Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi. You\'re my only hope. Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi. You\'re my only hope. Oh, he says it\'s nothing, sir. Merely a malfunction. Old data. Pay it no mind. Who is she? She\'s beautiful. I\'m afraid I\'m not quite sure, sir. Help me, Obi-Wan Kenobi... I think she was a passenger on our last voyage. A person of some importance, sir -- I believe. Our captain was attached to... Is there more to this recording? Behave yourself, Artoo. You\'re going to get us in trouble. It\'s all right, you can trust him. He\'s our new master.</p>\r\n<p>Wake up! Wake up! We\'re doomed. Do you think they\'ll melt us down? Don\'t shoot! Don\'t shoot! Will this never end? Luke, tell Owen that if he gets a translator to be sure it speaks Bocce. It looks like we don\'t have much of a choice but I\'ll remind him. I have no need for a protocol droid. Sir -- not in an environment such as this -- that\'s why I\'ve also been programmed for over thirty secondary functions that... What I really need is a droid that understands the binary language of moisture vaporators. Vaporators! Sir -- My first job was programming binary load lifter...very similar to your vaporators. You could say... Do you speak Bocce? Of course I can, sir. It\'s like a second language for me...I\'m as fluent in... All right shut up! I\'ll take this one.</p>\r\n<p>Luke, take these two over to the garage, will you? I want you to have both of them cleaned up before dinner. But I was going into Toshi Station to pick up some power converters... You can waste time with your friends when your chores are done. Now come on, get to it! All right, come on! And the red one, come on. Well, come on, Red, let\'s go. Uncle Owen... Yeah?This R2 unit has a bad motivator. Look! Hey, what\'re you trying to push on us? Excuse me, sir, but that R2 unit is in prime condition. A real bargain. Uncle Owen... Yeah? What about that one? What about that blue one? We\'ll take that one. Yeah, take it away.</p>', '2021-04-21 18:28:35', '2021-04-26 17:25:35', 'Emilie', 'a1bea01c742bmarkus-spiske-8OyKWQgBsKQ-unsplash.jpg', '  Des lignes de codes inclinés vers le coin inférieur droit.  ');

